Warning: Mention of rape and child abuse.

Children conceived as a result of rape will soon be recognised as victims of crime in England and Wales, the government has said. 

People have shared their stories of being born to mothers who were raped and explain why they refuse to let the past dictate their lives in a new documentary. 

Tasnim, whose mum was a victim of child sexual exploitation, is one of those people. 

Tap the link in our bio to watch the full documentary. 

#BBCNews

Ten years ago, two bombs were detonated at the Boston Marathon, killing three people and injuring hundreds more.

When the brothers responsible for the bombs launched a second attack on police three days later, Watertown’s chief of police, Edward Deveau, was in charge of detaining them.

Now, he tells his story.

Tap the link in our bio to hear survivors give first-hand accounts from the attack.

#BostonMarathon #Police #BBCNews

Is there a cooler way to start the year than this? 🥶

Devotees of a shrine in Tokyo welcomed the new year with an ice-cold bath in an annual tradition that goes back 68 years.

Forty people took part in the event at Teppozu Inari Shrine on Sunday, where men and women donned loincloths and white gowns before plunging into water filled with ice blocks.

The Shinto ritual is said to purify the soul and bring good health in the new year.

#Japan #Shinto #IceBath

media.caption:
Sally Rooney says she will continue to support Palestine Action, despite the group being banned in the UK.
 
The author who lives in County Mayo, Ireland, and is known for her novels including Normal People, has pledged to donate earnings from her books and TV adaptations to the organisation. 
 
Palestine Action was proscribed last month under UK law, but not Irish Law, after activists broke into RAF Brize Norton and caused damage to two military planes.
 
Tap the link in @BBCNews’s bio to find out more.
 
#BBCNews

“I don’t think people realise that it hurts.”
 
Wayne Rooney, Kae Kurd and Kelly Somers discuss the racist abuse aimed at Bournemouth’s Antoine Semenyo at Anfield.

At least 10 people have been killed in Russian strikes across Ukraine, according to authorities.
 
The strikes come ahead of what Donald Trump has called a "big day" at the White House, where the US president will meet Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky and other key European leaders.
 
UK PM Keir Starmer, German Chancellor Friedrich Merz and French President Emmanuel Macron are among those attending the talks in Washington.
 
Earlier, Trump ruled out Ukraine joining the Nato military alliance and reclaiming Crimea, illegally annexed by Moscow in 2014, in a future peace deal to end the Russia-Ukraine war.
 
Tap the link in @BBCNews's bio to follow live updates on this story.
 
#Russia #Ukraine #BBCNews

Ukrainian President Zelensky can end Russia’s war “if he wants to”, but there will be “no going into Nato by Ukraine” as part of a peace deal, Donald Trump has said.
 
Hours before he was due to host Volodymyr Zelensky at the White House, the US president also said there would be “no getting back” the Crimean peninsula, which Moscow illegally annexed in 2014, eight years before launching its full-scale invasion.
 
Trump’s remarks follow his summit with Russian leader Vladimir Putin in Alaska that resulted in the US president dropping a demand for a ceasefire and calling instead for a permanent peace deal.
 
After arriving in the US late on Sunday, Zelensky repeated his call for allies’ effective security guarantees.
 
European leaders will join the talks in Washington in an unprecedented show of unity with Ukraine. 
 
Tap the link in @BBCNews’s bio to read more about the high-stake talks.
 
(📷 Getty Images, EPA, Reuters)
 
#BBCNews

Hundreds of thousands of people gathered in Tel Aviv to call for an end to the Gaza war and a deal to secure the release of hostages.

Organisers said the government's plans to seize control of Gaza City risked the lives of about 20 hostages still being held by Hamas.

A one-day national strike, demanded by the families of hostages and others opposed to the expansion of the war, closed roads, offices and universities in some areas. Nearly 40 people were arrested during the day.

Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu criticised the protests, saying they would "harden Hamas's stance" and would only slow down the release of the hostages.

Tap the link in @BBCNews's bio to read what the hostage's families have said.

#Israel #Gaza #MiddleEast #BBCNews

"They are innocent. Perhaps the most innocent of all creatures."
 
A recent court ban on feeding pigeons in public spaces in the western Indian city of Mumbai has become a major flashpoint between civic bodies, public health activists and bird lovers.
 
This month, hundreds of people clashed with police twice while protesting the closure of a decades-old pigeon feeding spot, or a kabutarkhana.

The crackdown has angered animal lovers and religious feeders, as pigeons are long woven into India's cultural fabric.
 
But authorities imposed the ban due to concerns about health hazards due to pigeon droppings.
 
Tap the link in @BBCNews's bio to find out which other locations have bans on feeding pigeons.
 
(📷 Getty)
 
#Pigeons #Mumbai #BBCNews

Dame Helen Mirren has said James Bond should be played by a man, even though she is "such a feminist".
 
The Oscar-winning actress has previously been quoted saying that the concept of James Bond was "born out of profound sexism", and that women have always been an "incredibly important part" of the secret service.
 
"You can't have a woman. It just doesn't work. James Bond has to be James Bond, otherwise it becomes something else," Dame Helen said in an interview with Saga Magazine. 
 
Amazon MGM Studios will produce the next iteration of the spy franchise, and said it was planning a "fresh" take on franchise but would honour the "legacy" of the "iconic character".
 
Tap the link in @BBCNews's bio to find out which other actors have pushed back on the idea of a woman playing Bond.
 
(Getty)
 
#HelenMirren #JamesBond #BBCNews

A light aircraft made an emergency landing on a golf course in Sydney. 

The plane crashed during a training flight on Sunday, with an instructor and student on board.

The pilot and passenger escaped without major injuries.

Tap the link in @BBCNews’s bio to read what is known about the incident so far. 

#EmergencyLanding #Aviation #Sydney #BBCNews

After a six-year battle, a verdict has been reached over the song Baby Shark.
 
The inescapably catchy tune is understood to be a children's folk song which originated in the US in the 1970s and popularised at summer camps. US composer Jonathan Wright recorded a version in 2011, which he posted on YouTube.
 
Five years later, South Korean company Pinkfong produced and posted a version of the song with the "doo doo doo doo doo doo" refrain. This version went on to become the most-viewed YouTube video of all time, inspiring countless adaptations, translations, and even a movie.
 
Wright claimed he owned the copyright of his version, but Pinkfong argued that its version was simply a different arrangement of the same original folk song, which is in the public domain.
 
Tap the link in @BBCNews’s bio to read what South Korea's Supreme Court ruled in favour of.
 
#BabyShark #BBCNews

Hurricane Erin has weakened to a category three hurricane as it moves across the Caribbean. 
 
The storm became a rare category five cyclone on Saturday, but meteorologists expect it to fluctuate in intensity as it develops over the next few days.
 
Tap the link in @BBCNews’s bio to read about Erin’s predicted path.
 
#HurricaneErin #Erin #BBCNews

Could this be the ultimate reno project? 🔨
 
When former software company CEO Mike Conner bought Thorne Island near Pembrokeshire in Wales in 2017, its abandoned fortress didn’t have electricity or running water.
 
The fort, built in the 1850s, was once known for its extravagant parties and weddings, but had been empty for 17 years.
 
But now, after Mike’s renovation, it has 40 beds, four en-suite bathrooms and its very own night club, and is back on the market for £3m ($4.6m).
 
Mike admitted that he didn’t know what he was getting himself in for, adding: “My wife was pretty cross when I first said I bought it.”
 
He described his time on the island as “incredible”, saying: “We all often live by a calendar of scheduled meetings, but the island is the complete opposite - it’s off grid. It feels real time, it feels like living.”
 
Tap the link in @BBCNews’s bio to read more about the unusual history of Thorne Island.
 
(📷 Strutt & Parker / Mike Conner)
 
#ThorneIsland #Wales #BBCNews

In Israel, a one-day general strike is under way in protest of the government’s plan to occupy Gaza City.
 
The stoppage was demanded by the families of hostages and others who say the expansion of the war puts the lives of Israelis being held by Hamas at greater risk.
 
Thousands of residents have fled Gaza City’s southern Zeitoun neighbourhood, where days of continuous Israeli bombardment have created a “catastrophic” situation, the city’s Hamas-run municipality has told the BBC.
 
The move to seize the territory’s largest city, and displace its population, has been condemned by the UN Security Council.
 
Israel previously strongly rejected criticism from world leaders after its security cabinet approved the plan to take control of Gaza City.
 
Tap the link in @BBCNews’s bio to read more on this story. 
 
#BBCNews
